b'' b'on these counts, the apocrapha falls short of the glory of god.' b"to quote unger's bible dictionary on the apocrapha:" b'1. they abound in historical and geographical inaccuracies and' b'anachronisms.' b'2. they teach doctrines which are false and foster practices' b'which are at variance with sacred scripture.' b'3. they resort to literary types and display an artificiality of' b'subject matter and styling out of keeping with sacred scripture.' b'4. they lack the distinctive elements which give genuine' b'scripture their divine character, such as prophetic power and' b'poetic and religious feeling.' b'' b'first, to point out the obvious: while would clearly be a highly' b'subjective issue, one would be hard pressed to point to another book' b"of the ot (or for that matter the nt) that doesn't, on some issues, in" b'some way, fail one or more of the first three of these tests.' b'' b'second, one factor the deuterocanonicals share is the lateness of' b"their composition. i don't recall the exact dating of all of the" b'books, but most --if not all-- were written after the latest of the' b'canonical books (i.e. daniel).' b'' b'furthermore, while the deuterocanonical may or may not have been' b'originally written in greek, they are clearly deeply _hellenistic_ in' b'nature. both of these features probably figured heavily in the' b'rejection of these books from the various canons.' b'' b'these may not be strict and uniformly applicable criteria by which to' b'judge the canonicity of these books, but, as these discussions have' b'shown, i think the one thing we can see is that there _are_ no purely' b'objective standards for determining canonicity.' b'' b'nichael' b";(and (funcall (get 'smurfy-smile-icon 'like-predicate) 'lisp) (sys::honk))" 